SIMPLE: osculate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Osculate
<hw>Os"cu*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Osculated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Osculating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>osculatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>osculari</ets> to kiss, fr.
<ets>osculum</ets> a little mouth, a kiss, dim. of <ets>os</ets> mouth.
See <er>Oral</er>, and cf. <er>Oscillate</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To kiss.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>To touch closely, so as to have a
common curvature at the point of contact. See <er>Osculation</er>,
2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Osculate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Osculate
<hw>Os"cu*late</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To kiss one
another; to kiss.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>To touch closely. See
<er>Osculation</er>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>To have characters in common with
two genera or families, so as to form a connecting link between them; to
interosculate. See <er>Osculant</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Osculation</ent>⟦br⟧
